Tokyo stocks opened flat on Monday after North Korea&#8217;s latest missile launch but drew support from last week&#8217;s fresh records on Wall Street.North Korea fired a short-range ballistic missile that landed in the Sea of Japan (East Sea), the US Pacific Command said.Japan said it may have landed in the country&#8217;s Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ) though it was still evaluating the situation.Prime Minister Shinzo Abe condemned the launch and vowed &#8220;concrete action&#8221; with the US to rein in North Korea.The benchmark Nikkei 225 index gained 0.05 percent, or 10.34 points, to 19,697.18 at the open, while the Topix index of all first-section issues edged up 0.04 percent, or 0.70 points, to 1,570.12.Wall Street on Friday marginally rose to new records.&#8221;The US economy is steady, and the equity market is getting support from the view that even if growth slows down, it won&#8217;t crumble,&#8221; Shoji Hirakawa, chief global strategist at Tokai Tokyo Research Institute, told Bloomberg News.Rising US shares are &#8220;giving a sense of security for Japanese stocks,&#8221; he said.In early Tokyo trading, Sharp, which announced on Friday it expects to return to profitability this year, rose 2.40 percent to 425 yen.Toshiba gained 3.63 percent to 267.8 yen, while mobile carrier SoftBank fell 1.35 percent to 8,777 yen.The dollar edged down to 111.23 yen from 111.32 yen in New York Friday.-AFP